															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kakroom" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2198340); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2198340&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610225122" alt="Kakroom" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2198340)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kakroom" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2198340); return false;" >Kakroom</a></span> <span class="odate time_1503284941 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">21 Aug 2017 03:09</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3574977">
									

<p>Really liked this. Felt contemplative and peaceful, and you managed to strike an interesting balance between heartwarming and creepy. There's something very intrinsically beautiful about the machine made for war relenting after realizing the futility of vengeance - even when the possibility of achieving that vengeance was conceived by chance. It doesn't overstay its welcome, and it manages to build both characters to the point just where you can end it on something of a bittersweet note. I couldn't find any reasonably awkward structural flaws or grammatical issues; at the end of the day, if this is an epilogue, it feels like a very fitting one.</p>

							</div>

								
					
