		<div class="post" id="post-4839002">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,4839002)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-4839002">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/gaffsey" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(6590029); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=6590029&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610225122" alt="Gaffsey" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=6590029)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/gaffsey" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(6590029); return false;" >Gaffsey</a></span> <span class="odate time_1607360307 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">07 Dec 2020 16:58</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4839002">
									

<blockquote>
<p>leaves along time for things to kind of fade and become distant through reflection, hence Hector's coldness</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This kind of gets to my emerging issue with the portrayal of robots/AI in this canon: that they're too human, or at least assumed to be. I feel like when you take something that is, at least practically, indistinguishable from a human, then give it perfect recall, or the ability to tell the future, or a complete absence of aging, you don't just get a human plus those things, but an entirely different experience.</p>
<p>To steal a line from Neil Postman, if you take an ecosystem and add caterpillars to it, you don't get that ecosystem with caterpillars; you get a new ecosystem.</p>
<p>The AI's are presumably intended to evoke empathy through their resemblance to humans (and they do it quite well), but I can't help but feel that there's a lot of territory that could still be explored regarding what it is to be alive without falling back into the trope of anthropocentrism.</p>
<p>As for the tale itself, it's fine. I feel like so much has happened between reading the original tales and now that it's hard to feel all that much of a connection with the bot-soul. No voting for now.</p>

							</div>

								
